# 3. Terminology
 
| Term | Definition |
|------|-----------|
| **Sensory System** | A Layer 0 component that receives raw observation data and produces rich, general-purpose structured output. Analogous to a biological sensory organ. Senses transduce; they do not interpret. |
| **Cognitive Module** | A Layer 2 component that consumes sensory outputs and produces specialized interpretations. Analogous to a cortical processing region. |
| **Workspace** | The shared communication space through which broadcasts propagate. Analogous to the global workspace in GWT. |
| **Packet** | A single CRP message. Can be a broadcast, direct message, response, or override. |
| **Broadcast** | A packet sent to all cognitive modules simultaneously (target = "*"). |
| **Direct** | A packet sent to a specific module (target = module_id). |
| **Cycle** | One complete sense → prime → affect → broadcast → response → aggregate loop. One "frame" of conscious processing. |
| **Salience** | A computed score representing how much attention an observation deserves. |
| **Consciousness Threshold** | The salience level at which information transitions from background processing to twin-level awareness. Twin-specific and learned. |
| **Context Frame** | A compact packet of relevant memories assembled by the memory substrate based on sensory outputs. Attached to every broadcast. |
| **Volatile RAM** | Working memory with channel-dependent decay. Information persists for different durations based on cognitive significance. |
| **Instinct** | A QUERY response from a module that has detected partial relevance but cannot produce a full interpretation. Persists across cycles until resolved or decayed. |
| **Affect** | Emotional/perceptual metadata (valence, arousal, familiarity, urgency) that accompanies every broadcast and modulates cognitive module priorities. |
 
