# 5. Layer 0: Sensory Systems
 
Sensory systems receive raw observation data and produce structured, general-purpose output. They transduce — they do not interpret. A sensory system that detects a red indicator reports "dominant color: red, intensity: high" — it does not report "error detected." Interpretation is the cognitive layer's job.
 
## 5.1 Reference Sensory Systems
 
| Sense | Input | Output | Sub-Components |
|-------|-------|--------|----------------|
| **Visual** | Screenshot/pixels | Color distribution, layout structure, element density, icon/badge presence, modal detection, change delta from prior frame | Color analyzer, spatial layout classifier, element detector, change detector |
| **Textual** | Extracted text / OCR | Entity list (names, dates, numbers, codes), structural patterns (form, table, prose, code), information density, language register (clinical, casual, formal), anomalous fragments | Entity recognizer, structure classifier, density estimator, register detector |
| **Temporal** | Timestamps, intervals | Time-on-page, click velocity, navigation rhythm, session duration, time-of-day bucket, pace deviation from user baseline | Pace tracker, rhythm analyzer, session profiler |
| **Contextual** | App metadata, URL, title | App identity, app category, workspace/project context, navigation state, URL parameters, tab count | App classifier, workspace detector, nav state tracker |
| **Auditory** | Audio stream / transcript | Speech transcription, speaker count, ambient noise level, conversation vs. monologue, emotional prosody, keyword detection | Transcriber, speaker diarizer, prosody analyzer |
 
## 5.2 Sensory Output Contract
 
Each sensory system MUST produce a structured output conforming to:
 
```typescript
interface SensoryOutput {
  sense_id: string;           // e.g., "visual", "textual", "temporal"
  timestamp: string;          // ISO 8601
  observation_id: string;     // Links to the triggering observation
  data: Record<string, any>;  // Sense-specific structured output
  confidence: number;         // 0.0-1.0, overall confidence in the output
  processing_time_ms: number; // How long transduction took
}
```
 
## 5.3 Sensory System Requirements
 
- Sensory systems MUST run in parallel (not sequentially)
- Sensory systems MUST complete within their declared timeout (recommended: <100ms)
- Sensory systems MUST NOT interpret — they report what they detect, not what it means
- Sensory systems MUST produce output even when input is sparse (with lower confidence)
- Sensory systems SHOULD be stateless or minimally stateful (history for familiarity comparison is acceptable)
 
