# 7. Packet Format
 
Every CRP message conforms to the following schema:
 
```typescript
interface CRPPacket {
  // ─── Identity ─────────────────────────────────────
  packet_id: string;          // UUID v4, unique per packet
  cycle_id: string;           // UUID v4, groups all packets in one cycle
  timestamp: string;          // ISO 8601 with milliseconds
 
  // ─── Routing ──────────────────────────────────────
  type: PacketType;           // "broadcast" | "direct" | "response" | "override" | "resolve"
  source_module: string;      // ID of sending module (or "workspace" for broadcasts)
  target_module: string;      // "*" for broadcast, specific module_id for direct
 
  // ─── Context ──────────────────────────────────────
  observation_id: string;     // UUID of the triggering observation
  twin_id: string;            // UUID of the twin this packet belongs to
 
  // ─── Payload ──────────────────────────────────────
  payload: any;               // Module-specific content
  sensory_context: Record<string, SensoryOutput>;  // All sensory outputs (v0.2.0)
  memory_context: ContextFrame;                     // Pre-loaded memory (v0.2.0)
 
  // ─── Affect ───────────────────────────────────────
  affect: AffectContext;      // Emotional metadata (REQUIRED on broadcasts)
 
  // ─── Priority & Lifecycle ─────────────────────────
  priority: number;           // 0.0-1.0
  ttl: number;                // Time-to-live in cycles. 0 = this cycle only. -1 = persist until resolved.
  response_type?: ResponseType;
 
  // ─── Memory Tagging ───────────────────────────────
  memory_channel?: MemoryChannel;
  decay_hint?: DecayHint;
}
```
 
## 7.1 PacketType
 
```typescript
type PacketType =
  | "broadcast"   // Sent to all cognitive modules (target = "*")
  | "direct"      // Sent to a specific module
  | "response"    // Reply to a broadcast or direct
  | "override"    // High-priority interrupt that preempts normal processing
  | "resolve"     // Resolves a previously issued QUERY (instinct resolution)
```
 
## 7.2 ResponseType
 
```typescript
type ResponseType =
  | "assertion"   // Confident interpretation: "This is step 4 of payroll"
  | "query"       // Partial match / instinct: "Something looks off, need history"
  | "null"        // Not relevant. MUST NOT consume significant resources.
  | "override"    // Emergency preemption: "PHI detected — block NOW"
  | "resolve"     // Answering a previous query: "Here is the requested history"
```
 
### Response Type Semantics
 
**ASSERTION**: The module has a confident interpretation. Includes a confidence score (0.0-1.0). Assertions contribute to salience accumulation and may be stored in volatile RAM.
 
**QUERY (Instinct)**: The module detected a partial pattern match but lacks sufficient context for a full assertion. A QUERY persists across cycles as an "instinct." It includes a description of what additional information would resolve it. Other modules may respond with RESOLVE packets. Queries are stored in the `instinct` memory channel with no time-based decay — they persist until resolved or explicitly dismissed.
 
**NULL**: The observation is not relevant to this module. The module MUST NOT consume significant resources processing a null response. Null responses are not stored or propagated.
 
**OVERRIDE**: A safety-critical signal that preempts normal processing. Override packets are processed before all other responses. Only modules registered with `can_override: true` may issue overrides. Overrides trigger immediate action without waiting for the full cycle to complete. All overrides are stored in the `override` memory channel for audit.
 
**RESOLVE**: A response to a previously issued QUERY. References the original query's `packet_id`. When a QUERY receives a RESOLVE, the instinct is either promoted to an ASSERTION (if the resolution confirms relevance) or discarded.
 
## 7.3 AffectContext
 
```typescript
interface AffectContext {
  valence: number;      // -1.0 (negative/threatening) to 1.0 (positive/safe)
  arousal: number;      // 0.0 (calm/routine) to 1.0 (activated/urgent)
  familiarity: number;  // 0.0 (novel/unexpected) to 1.0 (known pattern)
  urgency: number;      // 0.0 (can wait) to 1.0 (immediate action required)
}
```
 
The workspace uses affect to dynamically adjust cognitive module priority weights before distributing the broadcast. Under negative valence + high arousal (threat), safety modules receive boosted priority. Under high familiarity + low arousal (routine), learning modules receive boosted priority. The specific adjustments are twin-specific and learned (see Section 10).
 
## 7.4 MemoryChannel
 
```typescript
type MemoryChannel =
  | "task"        // Active task context.     Half-life: ~10 minutes.
  | "anomaly"     // Detected anomalies.      Half-life: ~1 hour.
  | "instinct"    // Unresolved instincts.    No time decay. TTL or resolution only.
  | "learning"    // Pattern candidates.      Half-life: ~30 minutes.
  | "peripheral"  // Low-salience background. Half-life: ~1 minute.
  | "override"    // Safety/privacy overrides. Half-life: ~24 hours. Audit trail.
```
 
## 7.5 DecayHint
 
```typescript
interface DecayHint {
  initial_strength: number;          // 0.0-1.0
  decay_function: "exponential" | "linear" | "step";
  half_life_ms: number;
  promote_threshold?: number;        // If strength rises above this via recalls, promote
  emotional_weight?: number;         // High emotional events decay slower
}
```
 
