# 13. Transport
 
CRP is transport-agnostic:
 
- **In-process event bus**: TypeScript EventEmitter for modules in the same process (reference implementation)
- **HTTP/REST**: For cloud-hosted modules. Higher latency, suitable for non-time-critical cognition.
- **WebSocket**: For modules running as separate local processes
- **gRPC**: For high-throughput production deployments
 
The transport layer MUST preserve packet ordering within a single cycle. Packets from different cycles MAY arrive out of order.
 
### Deployment Topology
 
| Mode | Senses | Memory | Affect | Cognition |
|------|--------|--------|--------|-----------|
| **Full Local** | Local | Local RAM | Local | Local |
| **Hybrid** | Local | Local + Cloud | Local | Cloud |
| **Full Cloud** | Cloud | Cloud (Redis) | Cloud | Cloud |
 
In Hybrid mode, sensory systems and affect run locally. Cognitive modules run in the cloud, receiving compact sensory context (structured data, not raw pixels) as input.
 
---
 
# 14. Security Considerations
 
- Modules MUST NOT modify packets from other modules
- OVERRIDE capability MUST be restricted to explicitly authorized modules
- Raw observation data (screenshots) MUST NOT be included in packets transmitted over network transports. Only structured sensory outputs may cross network boundaries.
- The memory substrate MUST encrypt PHI-containing entries at rest
- Third-party modules MUST declare data handling practices in registration
- The workspace MUST log all OVERRIDE actions for audit
- Module execution MUST be sandboxed — a misbehaving module cannot crash the workspace
 
